Let $D$ be the vertex of the square on $\overline{AB}$, let $E$ be the vertex of the square on $\overline{BC}$, and let $F$ be the vertex of the square on $\overline{AC}$.  Let $s$ be the side length of the square.

[asy]
defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
size(4cm,4cm);

pair A,B,C,D,E,F;

A=(0,0);
B=(2,3);
C=(7,0);
D=(2/3)*B+(1/3)*A;
E=(2/3)*B+(1/3)*C;
F=(1.339,0);

draw(A--B--C--A);
draw(D--E--F--cycle);

label("$A$",B,N);
label("$B$",A,SW);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",E,NE);
label("$F$",F,S);
[/asy]

Triangles $ABD$ and $BCE$ are similar, so $\frac{AD}{BD} = \frac{BC}{BE}$.  Since $AD = BD = s$, we have $\frac{s}{s} = \frac{8}{BE}$, so $BE = 8$.

Similarly, triangles $ACF$ and $BCE$ are similar, so $\frac{AF}{CF} = \frac{BC}{BE}$.  Since $AF = CF = s$, we have $\frac{s}{s} = \frac{8}{8}$, so $CF = 8$.

Thus, $AC = AF + CF = 8 + 8 = 16$.  By the Pythagorean Theorem, $AC = \sqrt{6^2 + 8^2} = 10$.  Therefore, $s = \frac{1}{2} AC = \boxed{\frac{8}{5}}$.

